    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if mechanical tension is the main thing, how does that actually work on a microscopic level? like what's happening inside the muscle when that tension is applied? is it just the fibers stretching or is there more to the process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When sufficient mechanical tension is applied, the force pulls on the contractile proteins within the muscle fibers, known as myofibrils. This mechanical strain initiates a cascade of cellular signals within the muscle cells. These signals activate pathways that trigger satellite cells to fuse with existing fibers, leading to the synthesis of new contractile proteins like actin and myosin. Ultimately, this process causes the muscle fibers to physically thicken and grow larger.",
      "source": "target",
