    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok so you mention these tiny things like actin and myosin and these satellite cells... it's hard for me to picture it. is it basically like a bunch of little structures working together to build things up? like how they actually move or react to the tension?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Think of actin and myosin as tiny molecular motors that slide past each other to create force, much like ropes pulling against each other. When tension is applied, this pulling motion causes micro-tears in the muscle structure. Satellite cells act as the body's repair crew, recognizing this damage and donating their nuclei to help rebuild and reinforce the damaged fibers, making them bigger and stronger next time. It is a coordinated rebuilding effort at the microscopic level.",
      "source": "target",
